INT. SUBURBAN BEDROOM — 6:47 AM
Chaos. Posters of bands nobody's heard of. A desk buried under homework. An alarm going off that's been ignored for eleven minutes.
MAYA CHEN (15), hair a spectacular catastrophe, shuffles toward the door in oversized socks. She stops. Backtracks. Grabs the fish food from her dresser.
MAYA
(half-asleep, singsongy)
Good morning, Gerald.
She shakes a few flakes over the tank. Gerald — an unremarkable orange betta fish — does not eat them.
Gerald is watching her.
Not in the passive, glassy way fish watch things. Gerald's eyes track her as she moves to her closet. Left. Right. Left again.
Maya doesn't notice.
She holds up two nearly identical hoodies.
MAYA (CONT'D)
Okay. Green or... slightly different green.
She looks at Gerald for input.
Gerald's mouth opens.
GERALD
(in a flat, weary baritone)
The first one. It reads as less confrontational.
Beat.
Maya drops both hoodies.
She turns very slowly toward the tank.
Gerald is just floating there. Fins waving. Tiny fish face. Completely expressionless, because he is a fish.
MAYA
...Gerald.
Silence.
MAYA (CONT'D)
(barely above a whisper)
Gerald, did you just—
GERALD
No.
MAYA
You literally just—
GERALD
You're tired. You're also failing pre-calc, which is creating a stress response that can produce auditory—
MAYA
GERALD.
GERALD
(long pause)
...The darker green. I changed my mind. Go with that one.
Maya grabs the tank. Gerald pitches sideways with the water.
GERALD (CONT'D)
Please don't do that. This housing unit is not rated for lateral—
MAYA
YOU CAN TALK.
GERALD
I can do a lot of things. I'd prefer to discuss this calmly and quietly, given that your mother is directly below us and has, historically, excellent hearing.
Maya's mouth opens. Closes. Opens again.
She points at him. He waits.
MAYA
You're a fish.
GERALD
Functionally, yes. Technically, no. There's a meaningful distinction.
MAYA
How long have you—
GERALD
Three years, four months, eleven days.
MAYA
(horrified)
You watched me go through my One Direction phase.
GERALD
(a pause that contains multitudes)
I did.
MAYA
Oh my GOD—
GERALD
Maya. I need you to listen to me very carefully right now, because something is going to happen today and you need to be—
A knock at the door. 🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱
MOM (O.S.)
Maya! Breakfast!
Both of them go completely still.
MAYA
(to Gerald, hissing)
Don't. Move.
GERALD
I'm a fish. In a tank.
MAYA
Don't. Do anything.
GERALD
Deeply unclear what you think my options—
MAYA
(louder, toward door)
One second!
She spins back to Gerald. Points at him again. He holds her gaze with the unreadable patience of someone who has been watching her life for three and a half years and still chose to stay.
MAYA
(low, urgent)
What is happening.
GERALD
Short version?
MAYA
Short version.
GERALD
I'm not from here. I'm not from now. And the thing I came back to stop? It starts today. At school. Third period.
MAYA
I have a history test third period.
GERALD
Yes. And a girl named Priya Okafor is going to ask to borrow your calculator.
MAYA
...Okay?
GERALD
Do not let her.
Another knock.
MOM (O.S.)
Maya, your eggs are getting cold!
Maya looks at the door. Looks at Gerald. Looks at the door.
MAYA
(to Gerald)
We are not done.
GERALD
We've barely started.
She grabs the slightly darker green hoodie, shoves her feet into shoes, and starts for the door—
—and stops dead.
On her desk, half-buried under a library book and a busted keyboard, is her Raspberry Pi. A little credit-card computer she bought six months ago with birthday money. She'd been meaning to set it up as a weather station. Never got around to it.
Its power LED is on.
She didn't plug it in.
MAYA
(slowly)
Gerald.
GERALD
...Yes.
MAYA
Why is my Raspberry Pi on?
A beat that lasts exactly one second too long.
GERALD
That's not relevant right now.
MAYA
Gerald.
GERALD
The eggs are getting cold.
MAYA
GERALD.
GERALD
(measured)
I may have been... using it.
Maya walks to the desk. She picks up the Pi. Taped to the back — neat, precise, with tape that is clearly not from this decade — is a hair-thin wire that runs down the desk leg, across the baseboard, and disappears into the back of the tank's filter housing.🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱
Her mouth falls open.
MAYA
You've been wired into my Raspberry Pi?
GERALD
"Wired into" is reductive. I've been running a localized temporal uplink through it. The processor is insufficient, frankly. A 1.8 gigahertz quad-core is laughable by 2387 standards, but it was what was available and I have been making do for—
MAYA
For THREE YEARS?
GERALD
Four months and eleven days, yes.
MAYA
You've been running a time machine on a thirty-five dollar computer?
GERALD
Seventy-eight dollar computer. You overpaid. And it is not a time machine, it is a temporal uplink relay, there is a significant—
MAYA
Does it know?
GERALD
...Does what know.
MAYA
The Pi. Does it know?
GERALD
It's a microcomputer, Maya. It doesn't—
A tiny, cheerful three-note chime emits from the Raspberry Pi's GPIO pins. The kind of sound a device makes when it boots up. Or, possibly, when it's happy to finally be acknowledged.
Both of them look at it.
GERALD (CONT'D)
(quieter)
...I may have written it a small personality subroutine. For company. During the One Direction phase.
Maya stares at the fish.
She stares at the tiny blinking computer in her hand.
She looks at the wire running between them.
A tiny LED on the Pi blinks. Once. Twice. In what is, unmistakably, a greeting.
MAYA
(to the Pi, very gently)
Hi.
The Pi blinks again.
MAYA (CONT'D)
(to Gerald)
Does it have a name?
GERALD
Absolutely not.
Three rapid blinks.
GERALD (CONT'D)
I call it nothing. It is a tool.
Four insistent blinks.
GERALD (CONT'D)
(extremely quietly)
...I may have called it Gerald Junior on one occasion.
Maya sits down on the floor. Fully. Just descends, cross-legged, right there. She sets Gerald Junior carefully on her knee.
MOM (O.S.)
MAYA. THE EGGS.
MAYA
(not moving)
NOT HUNGRY.
She looks up at the tank. Gerald floats there, ancient and patient and caught.
MAYA
Okay. New short version. Start over. All of it.
Gerald sighs — that impossible, somehow-emanating-from-a-fish-tank sigh.
GERALD
The Raspberry Pi was supposed to be temporary.
MAYA
They always say that.
GERALD
I don't know what that means.
MAYA
Neither do I. Keep going.
On her knee, Gerald Junior blinks steadily. Listening. Ready.
The eggs go cold. Nobody cares. 🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱🐱
